"1015","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1079":"1079","about 1025":"omkring 1025","1054":"1054","0967":"0967","Powys, Merioneth, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"nl":{"1004–1027":"1004–1027","1015–Male":"1015–Overleden","1004–1054":"1004–1054","1018–Female":"1018–Overleden","1025–Male":"1025–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","0967–Male":"0967–Overleden","0970–1079":"0970–1079","1018":"1018","1027":"1027","1004":"1004","0970":"0970","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1079":"1079","about 1025":"circa 1025","1054":"1054","0967":"0967","Powys, Merioneth, Wales":"Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"1004–1027":"1004–1027","1015–Male":"1015–Deceased","1004–1054":"1004–1054","1018–Female":"1018–Deceased","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","0967–Male":"0967–Deceased","0970–1079":"0970–1079","1018":"1018","1027":"1027","1004":"1004","0970":"0970","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1079":"1079","about 1025":"about 1025","1054":"1054","0967":"0967","Powys, Merioneth, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tangno","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Domenic, Gioia, Raffaela, Rocco, Vito.","Italian: probably from a personal name of ancient Germanic origin composed with the element <i>thank</i> ‘thought’ (see   Tancredi  ); alternatively, perhaps in some cases, from the Italian Greek name <i>Tangos</i>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Tancredi","meanings":["from <i>thank</i> ‘thought’ + <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’."]},{"name":"Tangorra","meanings":["Italian (Apulia): perhaps a derivative of   Tango  ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Cadfael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>mael</i> ‘prince’. The detective monk Brother Cadfael features in a series of novels by  Ellis Peters ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Powys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Powis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Powis","meanings":["Welsh (now mainly West Midlands of England): habitational name from the region of Powis in mid Wales (from Old Welsh <i>powes</i> ‘country dwellers’)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Tangno ap Cadfael of Powys was born in 1004, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cadfael ap Lludd, was 37 and his mother, Nest Ferch Gwrgan, was 35. He married Meredith Ychan verch Meredith in 1024, in Merionethshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1027, in his hometown, at the age of 23."},"et":{"1004–1027":"1004–1027","1015–Male":"1015–Surnud","1004–1054":"1004–1054","1018–Female":"1018–Surnud","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","0967–Male":"0967–Surnud","0970–1079":"0970–1079","1018":"1018","1027":"1027","1004":"1004","0970":"0970","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1079":"1079","about 1025":"umbes 1025","1054":"1054","0967":"0967","Powys, Merioneth, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1004–1027":"1004–1027","1015–Male":"1015–Kuollut","1004–1054":"1004–1054","1018–Female":"1018–Kuollut","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","0967–Male":"0967–Kuollut","0970–1079":"0970–1079","1018":"1018","1027":"1027","1004":"1